<h3 class="title">Class Announcements</h3><br/>
<h2 class="date">January 21, 2014</h2>
<div class="blogbody">
<h3 class="title">Readings for Thursday</h3>
<p> For Thursday, please read and discuss the relationship between some subset of the following three papers:
<ul>
<li>Tomas Mikolov, Wen-足tau Yih, and Geoffrey Zweig. <a href="http://research.microsoft.com/pubs/189726/rvecs.pdf">Linguistic Regularities in Continuous Space Word Representations</a>. In Proceedings of NAACL HLT, 2013.

<li> Richard Socher;余 Jeffrey Pennington;余 Eric H. Huang;Andrew Y. Ng;Christopher D. Manning
<a href="http://aclweb.org/anthology//D/D11/D11-1014.pdf">Semi-足Supervised Recursive Autoencoders for Predicting Sentiment Distributions.</a> In Proceedings of EMNLP 2011.
 
<li> Turian, J., Ratinov, L., & Bengio, Y. (2010, July). <a href="http://aclweb.org/anthology//P/P10/P10-1040.pdf">Word representations: a simple and general method for semi-supervised learning.</a> In Proceedings of the 48th Annual Meeting of the Association for Computational Linguistics (pp. 384-394). Association for Computational Linguistics.
</ul>
<p> Here are two extra "older" papers 
<ul>
<li>  Elman, J. L. 1991. <a href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/~hwa/cs3730/elman1991.pdf">Distributed representations, simple recurrent networks, and grammatical structures</a>. Machine Learning, 7(2-3):195-225.
<li>  Pollack, J. B. 1990. <a href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/~hwa/cs3730/pollack1990.pdf">Recursive distributed representations.</a> Artificial Intelligence,46:77-105, November.
</ul>
<p> Please email me your comments by <b>9pm, Wednesday night</b>.  

<h3 class="title">First reading</h3>
<p> For our first paper, we've read 
<ul>
<li>R. Collobert, J. Weston, L. Bottou, M. Karlen, K. Kavukcuoglu and P. Kuksa. Natural Language Processing (Almost) from Scratch, Journal of Machine Learning Research (JMLR), 2011.
</ul>
<p> Great reading reactions, everyone! I will share your comments with the rest of the class via Google Document later tonight if I don't hear any objections.
</div>

<h2 class="date">January 16, 2014</h2>
<div class="blogbody">
<h3 class="title">Paper Selection</h3>
<p> Please take a look at the current list of potential papers and let me know which ones you are particularly interested in reading and discussing with the rest of the class. You should have received a Google Doc link from me via email. If you are having trouble opening up the link, please let me know.
</div>

<h2 class="date">January 7, 2014</h2>
<div class="blogbody">
<h3 class="title">Introduction</h3>
<p>Welcome to CS3730/ISSP3170. This term, our advanced seminar on Natural Language Processing does not have a pre-determined topic choice. Instead, we will come together as a class and decide the set of topics we wish to explore. We will take the first couple of weeks of class to get to know everyone's research interest, and come up with a set of papers to read and discuss for the rest of the term.  
</div>
